node.text: On the coast of Portugal, Gordon Ramsay visits one of the most unique vineyards on the planet where the vines grow in the sand. A new season of Gordon Ramsay: Uncharted airs Monday, May 31 at 9/8c.

node.title: Gordon Ramsay: Uncharted – A Vineyard in the Sand

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by National Geographic Travel on July 23, 2021. May be an image of twilight, nature, sky and ocean.

node.text:
Photo by @joshuacogan / The windblown, wild coast of Cape Henlopen State Park in Lewes, Delaware, is a place where the land and ocean battle back and forth. Grinding Atlantic winds and currents have changed this coast over millennia, creating unique and underappreciated ecosystems. Here, the aptly named Harbor of Refuge lighthouse sits just inside the bay on the northern edge of the park. 
To see more images of travels around the world, follow me @joshuacogan.

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by National Geographic Travel on July 23, 2021. May be an image of sky, mountain and nature.

node.text:
Photo by @daisygilardini / The majestic peaks of the Cordillera Paine in Chile’s Torres del Paine National Park are lit by the first morning rays, beautifully reflected on Lake Pehoé. To achieve the silky effect on the water’s surface, I used a neutral-density filter at an exposure of 2.5 seconds, with an aperture of f/22 at ISO 50.
Follow me @daisygilardini for more images and behind-the-scenes stories. #landscapephotography #TorresdelPaine #Chile #sunrise #Patagonia

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by National Geographic Travel on July 22, 2021. May be an image of 1 person and body of water.

node.text:
Photo by @hannahreyesmorales / A spear fisherman lights up a gray day out at sea. I've met some remarkable fisherfolk out here in the islands of the Philippines. For our archipelago, located in the center of the world's marine biodiversity, fishing is a way of life for coastal communities. They know the language of the sea, they help scientists identify species of fish, and they understand weather patterns intimately by looking toward the horizon. They are also among the first to witness the devastation happening in our oceans. 
Follow me @hannahreyesmorales for more stories from the Philippines and beyond. #Surigao #fishing #Philippines

node.text: Photo by @mattborowick / If you are looking for a beautiful drive this summer only a few hours from Denver, Colorado, I recommend Independence Pass. It has an elevation just over 12,000 feet (3,658 meters) and is on the Continental Divide, making for an incredible and mountainous journey ending in Aspen. Please follow @mattborowick for more pictures like this. #colorado #mountains #nature #adventure #independencepass

node.text: Photo by Keith Ladzinski @ladzinski / A dewdrop balances between blades of grass in a meadow in Boulder, Colorado. Dew is formed from condensed water vapor in areas less susceptible to radiated heat, like those with grass and other vegetation.

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by National Geographic Travel on July 22, 2021. May be an image of outdoors.

node.text:
Photo by @jimrichardsonng / The abandoned village on St. Kilda runs along the bay in one long “street.” The newer houses in the foreground date back only a couple of centuries, while the older black houses running up the hill are much older. Among them the rounded cleits were used for drying seabirds (fulmars, gannets, and puffins), the islanders' main supply of food. The National Trust for Scotland has replaced roofs on a few of the houses, which are now used by their work crews who come to the islands in the summer. 
For more Scotland, follow me @JimRichardsonNG.

node.text:
Photo by @daisygilardini / I captured this image in late November in Manitoba’s Wapusk National Park. The bear is waiting patiently for the pack ice to form. Once the ice is strong enough to support his weight over long distances, he will venture over distant horizons, looking for seals. 
Polar bear lives are broken into two seasons. The first is winter, the feasting season, when bears hunt seals while roaming on the pack ice. And then there is summer, the fasting season, when the absence of ice pushes the bears onto land, with scarce food sources. During this time, their diet is poor and consists mainly of birds’ eggs and kelp. Occasionally they will find a whale carcass on the beach.
Follow me @daisygilardini for more images and behind-the-scenes stories. #wapusknationalpark #polarbear #conservation #climatechange

node.text:
Photo by @joshuacogan / This particular part of Tongass National Forest on Alaska's Prince of Wales Island is thought to hold some of the largest old-growth trees in the forest. I've been following those who are mapping these giant trees for a number of years as a means to understand the relationship between the trees and mycelial networks that underpin them. 
To journey along as I search for some of these remaining "mother trees," follow me @joshuacogan.

node.text: Photo by @kahliaprilphoto / When the temperatures rise in the Rockies, the waterways turn into raging torrents, bulging with meltwater that started as snow high up on the mountain summits.
